{"title":"Venir/être/aller","markdown":{"yaml":{"title":"Venir/être/aller","author":"Kunal Khurana","date":"02-07-2025","categories":["A1/A2","venir","être","aller","past","present","future"],"image":"venir+être.png"},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n\n\n<div style=\"text-align: left; padding: 10px;\">\n  <a href=\"mailto:info@frenchwithkunal.ca\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"margin: 0 10px; color: #000;\"><i class=\"fas fa-envelope fa-lg\"></i></a>\n  <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/kunal.khurana7\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"margin: 0 10px; color: #E1306C;\"><i class=\"fab fa-instagram fa-lg\"></i></a>\n  <a href=\"https://frenchwithkunal.ca\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"margin: 0 10px; color: #0077b5;\"><i class=\"fas fa-globe fa-lg\"></i></a>\n  <a href=\"https://whatsapp.com/channel/0029Vb57n2e7dmegpjYpyi3V\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"margin: 0 10px; color: #25D366;\"><i class=\"fab fa-whatsapp fa-lg\"></i></a>\n  <button onclick=\"copyLink()\" style=\"background-color: #0077b5; color: white; padding: 8px 16px; border: none; border-radius: 4px; cursor: pointer; margin-left: 10px;\">\n    <i class=\"fas fa-copy\"></i> \n  </button>\n  <span id=\"copy-message\" style=\"margin-left: 10px; color: green; display: none;\">Link copied!</span>\n</div>\n\n<script>\n  function copyLink() {\n    // Get the current page URL\n    const url = window.location.href;\n    \n    // Copy the URL to the clipboard\n    navigator.clipboard.writeText(url).then(() => {\n      // Show a confirmation message\n      const message = document.getElementById(\"copy-message\");\n      message.style.display = \"inline\";\n      setTimeout(() => {\n        message.style.display = \"none\";\n      }, 2000); // Hide the message after 2 seconds\n    });\n  }\n</script>\n\n\n\n::: {.content-visible when-profile=\"english\"}\nIn today’s [lecture](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1U2fPUfpGtQ562AUyCxQgT_wGu3U-B_tD/view?usp=drive_link), we explored three key verbs - venir, être en train de, and aller - and how they can help us talk about the past, present, and future without having to conjugate the second verb. This is such a game-changer because it simplifies sentence construction and makes navigating French so much easier.\n\nFor example:\n\nVenir de + infinitive lets you talk about something you just did (past).\n\nÊtre en train de + infinitive describes what you’re doing right now (present).\n\nAller + infinitive helps you talk about what you’re going to do (future).\n\nThese structures are incredibly handy, especially when you’re still getting comfortable with French conjugation. They’re like little shortcuts that make expressing yourself in French feel more natural and less overwhelming. If you’re learning French, I highly recommend practicing these with these verbs: [example_1](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1CPzcCDoKlz-lXpc6_OWU66hhKpLIV3kl/view?usp=drive_link), [example_2](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1qeVtIk-MSwEwhey2RUZBXe8GGJyzzCXK/view?usp=drive_link)- they’ll make a big difference!\n:::\n\n::: {.content-visible when-profile=\"french\"}\nAujourd’hui, [nous avons exploré](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1U2fPUfpGtQ562AUyCxQgT_wGu3U-B_tD/view?usp=drive_link) trois verbes clés - **venir**, **être en train de**, et **aller** — et comment ils peuvent nous aider à parler du passé, du présent et du futur sans avoir à conjuguer le deuxième verbe. C’est un vrai changement car cela simplifie la construction des phrases et rend la navigation en français beaucoup plus facile.\n\nPar exemple :\\\n- **Venir de** + infinitif permet de parler de quelque chose que l’on vient de faire (passé).\\\n- **Être en train de** + infinitif décrit ce que l’on est en train de faire (présent).\\\n- **Aller** + infinitif aide à parler de ce que l’on va faire (futur).\n\nCes structures sont incroyablement pratiques, surtout quand on commence à apprendre le français. Ce sont comme des raccourcis qui rendent l’expression en français plus naturelle et moins stressante. Si vous apprenez le français, je vous recommande fortement de les pratiquer avec ces verbes : [Exemple_1](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1CPzcCDoKlz-lXpc6_OWU66hhKpLIV3kl/view?usp=drive_link), [Exemple_2](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1qeVtIk-MSwEwhey2RUZBXe8GGJyzzCXK/view?usp=drive_link)- ils feront une grande différence dans votre apprentissage de la lanuge française!\n:::","srcMarkdownNoYaml":"\n\n\n<div style=\"text-align: left; padding: 10px;\">\n  <a href=\"mailto:info@frenchwithkunal.ca\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"margin: 0 10px; color: #000;\"><i class=\"fas fa-envelope fa-lg\"></i></a>\n  <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/kunal.khurana7\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"margin: 0 10px; color: #E1306C;\"><i class=\"fab fa-instagram fa-lg\"></i></a>\n  <a href=\"https://frenchwithkunal.ca\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"margin: 0 10px; color: #0077b5;\"><i class=\"fas fa-globe fa-lg\"></i></a>\n  <a href=\"https://whatsapp.com/channel/0029Vb57n2e7dmegpjYpyi3V\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"margin: 0 10px; color: #25D366;\"><i class=\"fab fa-whatsapp fa-lg\"></i></a>\n  <button onclick=\"copyLink()\" style=\"background-color: #0077b5; color: white; padding: 8px 16px; border: none; border-radius: 4px; cursor: pointer; margin-left: 10px;\">\n    <i class=\"fas fa-copy\"></i> \n  </button>\n  <span id=\"copy-message\" style=\"margin-left: 10px; color: green; display: none;\">Link copied!</span>\n</div>\n\n<script>\n  function copyLink() {\n    // Get the current page URL\n    const url = window.location.href;\n    \n    // Copy the URL to the clipboard\n    navigator.clipboard.writeText(url).then(() => {\n      // Show a confirmation message\n      const message = document.getElementById(\"copy-message\");\n      message.style.display = \"inline\";\n      setTimeout(() => {\n        message.style.display = \"none\";\n      }, 2000); // Hide the message after 2 seconds\n    });\n  }\n</script>\n\n\n\n::: {.content-visible when-profile=\"english\"}\nIn today’s [lecture](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1U2fPUfpGtQ562AUyCxQgT_wGu3U-B_tD/view?usp=drive_link), we explored three key verbs - venir, être en train de, and aller - and how they can help us talk about the past, present, and future without having to conjugate the second verb. This is such a game-changer because it simplifies sentence construction and makes navigating French so much easier.\n\nFor example:\n\nVenir de + infinitive lets you talk about something you just did (past).\n\nÊtre en train de + infinitive describes what you’re doing right now (present).\n\nAller + infinitive helps you talk about what you’re going to do (future).\n\nThese structures are incredibly handy, especially when you’re still getting comfortable with French conjugation. They’re like little shortcuts that make expressing yourself in French feel more natural and less overwhelming. If you’re learning French, I highly recommend practicing these with these verbs: [example_1](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1CPzcCDoKlz-lXpc6_OWU66hhKpLIV3kl/view?usp=drive_link), [example_2](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1qeVtIk-MSwEwhey2RUZBXe8GGJyzzCXK/view?usp=drive_link)- they’ll make a big difference!\n:::\n\n::: {.content-visible when-profile=\"french\"}\nAujourd’hui, [nous avons exploré](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1U2fPUfpGtQ562AUyCxQgT_wGu3U-B_tD/view?usp=drive_link) trois verbes clés - **venir**, **être en train de**, et **aller** — et comment ils peuvent nous aider à parler du passé, du présent et du futur sans avoir à conjuguer le deuxième verbe. C’est un vrai changement car cela simplifie la construction des phrases et rend la navigation en français beaucoup plus facile.\n\nPar exemple :\\\n- **Venir de** + infinitif permet de parler de quelque chose que l’on vient de faire (passé).\\\n- **Être en train de** + infinitif décrit ce que l’on est en train de faire (présent).\\\n- **Aller** + infinitif aide à parler de ce que l’on va faire (futur).\n\nCes structures sont incroyablement pratiques, surtout quand on commence à apprendre le français. Ce sont comme des raccourcis qui rendent l’expression en français plus naturelle et moins stressante. Si vous apprenez le français, je vous recommande fortement de les pratiquer avec ces verbes : [Exemple_1](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1CPzcCDoKlz-lXpc6_OWU66hhKpLIV3kl/view?usp=drive_link), [Exemple_2](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1qeVtIk-MSwEwhey2RUZBXe8GGJyzzCXK/view?usp=drive_link)- ils feront une grande différence dans votre apprentissage de la lanuge française!\n:::"},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":true,"freeze":true,"echo":true,"output":true,"warning":true,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"increment":true,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env":null,"code-fold":"none","code-overflow":"scroll","code-link":false,"code-line-numbers":false,"code-tools":false,"tbl-colwidths":"auto","merge-includes":true,"inline-includes":false,"preserve-yaml":false,"latex-auto-mk":true,"latex-auto-install":true,"latex-clean":true,"latex-min-runs":1,"latex-max-runs":10,"latex-makeindex":"makeindex","latex-makeindex-opts":[],"latex-tlmgr-opts":[],"latex-input-paths":[],"latex-output-dir":null,"link-external-icon":false,"link-external-newwindow":false,"self-contained-math":false,"format-resources":[],"notebook-links":true},"pandoc":{"standalone":true,"wrap":"none","default-image-extension":"png","to":"html","include-in-header":[{"text":"<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/font-awesome